 Good morning, church.

30
00:01:26,800 --> 00:01:27,800
 It's always good to be here.

31
00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:33,440
 And Yuen Long crew, and online if you're watching, Yuen Long, we are having the first gathering

32
00:01:33,440 --> 00:01:34,440
 in Yuen Long right now.

33
00:01:34,440 --> 00:01:37,000
 They're having a barbecue and live streaming the sermon, I believe.

34
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:42,560
 So yeah, that's very exciting for our church as we launch, start launching our way into

35
00:01:42,560 --> 00:01:45,320
 Yuen Long and all that God's doing there.

36
00:01:45,320 --> 00:01:49,480
 So yes, as Andrew's been saying, we spent the past few weeks exploring different faucets

37
00:01:49,480 --> 00:01:51,000
 of relationships.

38
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:54,920
 We've looked at how we can sacrificially give of ourselves, be a good neighbor to the ones

39
00:01:54,920 --> 00:01:55,920
 around us.

40
00:01:55,920 --> 00:02:00,800
 We looked at humility and how that countercultural it is in a city like Hong Kong.

41
00:02:00,800 --> 00:02:03,120
 We've talked about reaching out for others in the gospel.

42
00:02:03,120 --> 00:02:08,960
 Do we hide Jesus under a bushel or do we let Him shine in our lives as He's supposed to?

43
00:02:08,960 --> 00:02:12,360
 We're talking about, we've talked about as a community, how do we relate to each other

44
00:02:12,360 --> 00:02:14,640
 in our relationship with the Lord?

45
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:17,480
 And then last week, Carla talked to us about being reconcilers.

46
00:02:17,480 --> 00:02:22,180
 You know, are we willing to be reconciled to those who are different or even at animosity

47
00:02:22,180 --> 00:02:23,560
 with us?

48
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:24,920
 And it's been a good journey for me.

49
00:02:24,920 --> 00:02:26,640
 I hope it's been a good journey for you too.

50
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:30,800
 It's been a great honor working with my colleagues and building the sermon series.

51
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:34,320
 And so we do round up today by looking at family relationships.

52
00:02:34,320 --> 00:02:39,080
 I'm going to tell you something by saying this, something mysterious.

53
00:02:39,080 --> 00:02:43,800
 So I daydream a lot, always daydream about the most ridiculous things.

54
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:48,400
 I dream about myself being like a UFC champion and, you know, all that kind of stuff, grappling

55
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:50,720
 John Jones and choking him out.

56
00:02:50,720 --> 00:02:54,240
 I dream about receiving phone calls for some reason.

57
00:02:54,240 --> 00:02:57,280
 I always think, you know, when I pick up the phone, someone's going to call me and be like,

58
00:02:57,280 --> 00:03:00,960
 "Ellison, yes, we need you at the airport within the next 25 minutes.

59
00:03:00,960 --> 00:03:01,960
 Should you wish to confirm?"

60
00:03:01,960 --> 00:03:04,880
 You know, and then I'll be there at the airport and they send me on some special mission.

61
00:03:04,880 --> 00:03:11,240
 You know, but it gets me thinking, the ring of a telephone is one of the most mysterious

62
00:03:11,240 --> 00:03:13,120
 things in life, right?

63
00:03:13,120 --> 00:03:17,520
 Because you can never really guarantee what you might hear on the other end.

64
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:23,080
 We might have a good idea, for example, if my wife calls me around 4 to 5 p.m. in the

65
00:03:23,080 --> 00:03:27,200
 evening, I can almost guarantee that the conversation is going to go like, "Hey, what do you want

66
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:28,200
 to eat?"

67
00:03:28,200 --> 00:03:29,200
 "I don't know.

68
00:03:29,200 --> 00:03:30,200
 What do you want to eat?"

69
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:31,200
 "I don't know.

70
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:32,200
 What are you going to eat?"

71
00:03:32,200 --> 00:03:36,240
 Until I correctly guess what she wanted to eat and we go and eat that, okay?

72
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:40,200
 Thirteen years, it's been the same conversation.

73
00:03:40,200 --> 00:03:42,160
 But you never really know.

74
00:03:42,160 --> 00:03:45,800
 You never really know until you actually pick up the phone and every now and then you get

75
00:03:45,800 --> 00:03:51,200
 one of those phone calls that completely changes the trajectory of your life.

76
00:03:51,200 --> 00:03:54,120
 A few years ago, I got one of these phone calls.

77
00:03:54,120 --> 00:03:59,480
 So my wife, Brittany, and I, we just finished going through the process of becoming Project

78
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:01,360
 Bridge parents.

79
00:04:01,360 --> 00:04:07,040
 Now Project Bridge is a program by Mother's Choice that trains people to be foster care

80
00:04:07,040 --> 00:04:11,920
 families, to train up people to be foster care families so you can receive children

81
00:04:11,920 --> 00:04:16,560
 in your home, make sure they have a safe, healthy place until they're matched into their

82
00:04:16,560 --> 00:04:18,720
 forever families.

83
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:22,400
 And so we did the training because, you know, we had fostered a few children in the past,

84
00:04:22,400 --> 00:04:24,080
 three other children in the past.

85
00:04:24,080 --> 00:04:27,200
 We'd received them in their home and provided some foster care for them.

86
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:30,600
 But we'd never done any official training for that.

87
00:04:30,600 --> 00:04:31,600
 So we thought, "You know what?

88
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:32,760
 We'll do the training.

89
00:04:32,760 --> 00:04:37,600
 It seemed like a good thing to do and in case the need comes up again in the future, we

90
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:39,480
 would be able to do that."

91
00:04:39,480 --> 00:04:43,580
 But we never really expected the need to come up.

92
00:04:43,580 --> 00:04:47,280
 And so when we got the call that there was a one-month-old baby that needed a foster

93
00:04:47,280 --> 00:04:53,440
 home, to be honest, our reaction was a bit more like, "Oh, actually, I don't know."

94
00:04:53,440 --> 00:04:57,240
 I mean, we didn't know how long this child would be with us.

95
00:04:57,240 --> 00:04:59,960
 We had very little information at the time.

96
00:04:59,960 --> 00:05:01,320
 And you know, things were going well for us.

97
00:05:01,320 --> 00:05:02,580
 We were living smoothly.

98
00:05:02,580 --> 00:05:04,180
 We had holidays planned.

99
00:05:04,180 --> 00:05:07,080
 The home was nice and calm and tidy.

100
00:05:07,080 --> 00:05:08,900
 We had no major responsibilities.

101
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:10,760
 We were enjoying what you call dink life.

102
00:05:10,760 --> 00:05:12,680
 Do you know what dink means?

103
00:05:12,680 --> 00:05:14,240
 Double income, no kids.

104
00:05:14,240 --> 00:05:15,440
 Perfect, right?

105
00:05:15,440 --> 00:05:20,400
 We could just do whatever we want, whenever we wanted, not accountable to anybody.

106
00:05:20,400 --> 00:05:25,360
 And so receiving a child into the home just seemed like a giant disruption that we weren't

107
00:05:25,360 --> 00:05:27,840
 ready to engage with.

108
00:05:27,840 --> 00:05:32,520
 But when we got this phone call, it just so happened that it was during the Justice Conference,

109
00:05:32,520 --> 00:05:35,280
 the last Justice Conference we had in Hong Kong.

110
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:39,460
 And it just so happened that one of the keynote speakers at that Justice Conference was a

111
00:05:39,460 --> 00:05:42,020
 man called Dr. Krish Kandai.

112
00:05:42,020 --> 00:05:47,020
 And Krish Kandai, he lives in the UK, amongst many other things, has a huge heart for foster

113
00:05:47,020 --> 00:05:48,020
 care and adoption.

114
00:05:48,020 --> 00:05:52,660
 He himself welcomes many children into his home, has adopted many kids, and that was

115
00:05:52,660 --> 00:05:57,060
 exactly what he was talking about, the importance of foster care and adoption.

116
00:05:57,060 --> 00:05:59,740
 Now during that session, you know, I was running around doing different things.

117
00:05:59,740 --> 00:06:04,100
 Brittany and I weren't sitting together, but our reaction was exactly the same.

118
00:06:04,100 --> 00:06:08,140
 Tears down our eyes, we kind of found each other in the hallways, "Okay, let's do it,

119
00:06:08,140 --> 00:06:09,140
 let's do it, honey.

120
00:06:09,140 --> 00:06:13,660
 Yes, Jesus, we'll take this child, whatever it takes, we're going to do it."

121
00:06:13,660 --> 00:06:17,740
 And soon after that, we received baby Sam into our home.

122
00:06:17,740 --> 00:06:19,420
 This is baby Sam right here.

123
00:06:19,420 --> 00:06:21,820
 He was one month old from when we joined our home.

124
00:06:21,820 --> 00:06:24,300
 We picked him up from the hospital.

125
00:06:24,300 --> 00:06:28,820
 And so what followed was the most amazing nine months of looking after Sam, watching

126
00:06:28,820 --> 00:06:34,580
 him grow up, teaching him new things, celebrating his milestones, Christmas, Chinese New Year,

127
00:06:34,580 --> 00:06:36,240
 visit to Disneyland.

128
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:40,100
 We did all the things you would expect a family to do.

129
00:06:40,100 --> 00:06:44,220
 And I had no idea I could love a child I had just met so deeply.

130
00:06:44,220 --> 00:06:48,620
 I mean, from the moment I met baby Sam, I was done.

131
00:06:48,620 --> 00:06:51,380
 I held him in my arms, picked him up from the hospital.

132
00:06:51,380 --> 00:06:56,040
 It was like my heart was completely there with him.

133
00:06:56,040 --> 00:06:58,700
 But also during that time, we had to wrestle with a lot of questions.

134
00:06:58,700 --> 00:07:02,820
 People asked us questions like, you know, or gave us advice, very bad advice, like,

135
00:07:02,820 --> 00:07:06,460
 "Oh, you know, don't get too attached to him because it's going to be very sad when you

136
00:07:06,460 --> 00:07:07,460
 have to let him go."

137
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:09,140
 "Oh, it's going to be so difficult.

138
00:07:09,140 --> 00:07:11,020
 Do you guys think you can cope?"

139
00:07:11,020 --> 00:07:14,540
 Or, "How are you going to give him up in the future?"

140
00:07:14,540 --> 00:07:16,360
 You know, by the way, we never gave him up.

141
00:07:16,360 --> 00:07:20,660
 Never use those terms when you talk to foster care and adoption children, okay?

142
00:07:20,660 --> 00:07:22,260
 We're not giving children up.

143
00:07:22,260 --> 00:07:25,220
 They're being placed, adopted into a new home.

144
00:07:25,220 --> 00:07:27,800
 People would say things like, "Oh, I could never do that.

145
00:07:27,800 --> 00:07:30,300
 It would be too much."

146
00:07:30,300 --> 00:07:34,260
 But from our perspective, really, in the end, it wasn't even a choice.

147
00:07:34,260 --> 00:07:37,860
 If this child was going to be in our home, if we had said yes, we were going to love

148
00:07:37,860 --> 00:07:40,640
 this child with our whole hearts.

149
00:07:40,640 --> 00:07:45,300
 We were going to form good, healthy attachments to him and let him form good, healthy attachments

150
00:07:45,300 --> 00:07:50,580
 to us because this was the way this baby was going to learn what love is.

151
00:07:50,580 --> 00:07:55,260
 And I can honestly say Brittany and I, without any holding anything back, love that child

152
00:07:55,260 --> 00:08:00,340
 with our whole hearts, even though we knew his time with us would be temporary.

153
00:08:00,340 --> 00:08:04,020
 And not a lot of people in this room right here were part of that journey, walking alongside

154
00:08:04,020 --> 00:08:08,700
 with us, supporting us in our journey with baby Sam.

155
00:08:08,700 --> 00:08:10,500
 Did we think we could do it?

156
00:08:10,500 --> 00:08:11,580
 No.

157
00:08:11,580 --> 00:08:13,540
 Was it too much at times?

158
00:08:13,540 --> 00:08:14,540
 Yes.

159
00:08:14,540 --> 00:08:19,380
 But was it worth every ounce of our effort, love, and tears?

160
00:08:19,380 --> 00:08:20,380
 Absolutely.

161
00:08:20,380 --> 00:08:21,380
 100%.

162
00:08:22,380 --> 00:08:25,660
 Okay, so why am I telling you this story?

163
00:08:25,660 --> 00:08:28,220
 Well, a couple of things.

164
00:08:28,220 --> 00:08:31,900
 Firstly, November is Adoption Awareness Month.

165
00:08:31,900 --> 00:08:36,220
 All over the world this month, people and organizations are promoting the importance

166
00:08:36,220 --> 00:08:38,460
 of foster care and adoption.

167
00:08:38,460 --> 00:08:43,220
 And in Hong Kong, right at this moment, there's a huge need for this.

168
00:08:43,220 --> 00:08:47,620
 A news article came out not too long ago, you might have seen it, that said, "Over the

169
00:08:47,620 --> 00:08:51,300
 next few years, because of all the disruptions and all the families leaving that we've had

170
00:08:51,300 --> 00:08:56,340
 during protests and COVID and all the things we've been facing in this city, there's going

171
00:08:56,340 --> 00:09:01,100
 to be a 20% reduction," they believe, "in the amount of foster homes that are available

172
00:09:01,100 --> 00:09:08,020
 for children, leaving kids in need in a very vulnerable position."

173
00:09:08,020 --> 00:09:09,020
 But this is it, church.

174
00:09:09,020 --> 00:09:14,900
 This is where we have an opportunity to step up and literally make a dramatic, life-changing

175
00:09:14,900 --> 00:09:18,460
 difference in the lives of these children.

176
00:09:18,460 --> 00:09:23,620
 So the first thing I want to urge us today is this, ask ourselves this question, "Has

177
00:09:23,620 --> 00:09:27,260
 the Lord called you to adopt children?

178
00:09:27,260 --> 00:09:32,600
 Has the Lord called you to be foster parents, giving kids a safe home to live in before

179
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:35,400
 they are adopted into their forever families?

180
00:09:35,400 --> 00:09:40,220
 Or what else can I do to support this area of life?"

181
00:09:40,220 --> 00:09:44,740
 If even if you just have a little bit of an inkling, if you're just a little bit curious,

182
00:09:44,740 --> 00:09:46,180
 don't ignore that.

183
00:09:46,180 --> 00:09:49,380
 Be curious, as Carla said last week.

184
00:09:49,380 --> 00:09:52,340
 After all, this is literally a mandate from God.

185
00:09:52,340 --> 00:09:54,220
 God commands us to do this.

186
00:09:54,220 --> 00:09:59,140
 One James 2:7, "Religion that our God, our Father accepts as pure and faultless is this,

187
00:09:59,140 --> 00:10:04,100
 to look after orphans and widows in their distress and to keep oneself being polluted

188
00:10:04,100 --> 00:10:06,660
 by the world."

189
00:10:06,660 --> 00:10:08,700
 So find out more.

190
00:10:08,700 --> 00:10:10,180
 Ask people that have gone through that journey.

191
00:10:10,180 --> 00:10:14,380
 There are many families in our community that have gone through that, including Pastor Andrew

192
00:10:14,380 --> 00:10:18,460
 and Chris, and they would be more than happy to sit down with you to tell you about their

193
00:10:18,460 --> 00:10:22,560
 adoption journey and what God has placed on their hearts in this.

194
00:10:22,560 --> 00:10:26,460
 Because I'm not kidding when I say if the church got the act together, if followers

195
00:10:26,460 --> 00:10:32,220
 of Jesus really came together to do this, we could literally see every single child

196
00:10:32,220 --> 00:10:37,860
 in this city adopted or fostered in safe, healthy families.

197
00:10:37,860 --> 00:10:38,860
 That's a reality.

198
00:10:38,860 --> 00:10:43,460
 That's a goal that can actually be met by the people of God.

199
00:10:43,460 --> 00:10:50,420
 So think about this church and ask God, "What have I been called to do in this area?"

200
00:10:50,420 --> 00:10:55,540
 But as I was reflecting on this fact too, there's a deeper sort of theological truth

201
00:10:55,540 --> 00:11:00,140
 that comes into mind and that convicts me as I look at this.

202
00:11:00,140 --> 00:11:03,960
 And to explore a bit more about that, we're going to turn to Galatians chapter 4.

203
00:11:03,960 --> 00:11:07,460
 So if you can follow on the screen or if you have a Bible with you, you can open up to

204
00:11:07,460 --> 00:11:11,180
 Galatians chapter 4, verses 4 to 7.

205
00:11:11,180 --> 00:11:12,460
 Let me read this for you.

206
00:11:12,460 --> 00:11:18,740
 It says this, "But when the set time had fully come, God sent His Son, born of a woman,

207
00:11:18,740 --> 00:11:23,300
 born under the law, to redeem those under the law that we might receive adoption to

208
00:11:23,300 --> 00:11:26,000
 sonship or daughtership.

209
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:31,100
 Because you are His sons and daughters, God sent the spirit of His Son into our hearts,

210
00:11:31,100 --> 00:11:34,360
 the spirit who calls out, 'Abba, Father.'

211
00:11:34,360 --> 00:11:37,300
 So you are no longer a slave but God's child.

212
00:11:37,300 --> 00:11:42,880
 And since you are God's child, He has made you also an heir."

213
00:11:42,880 --> 00:11:47,760
 You see, we just talked about these vulnerable children who are in need of homes, in need

214
00:11:47,760 --> 00:11:52,180
 of someone to come and welcome them into a loving, safe family.

215
00:11:52,180 --> 00:11:57,340
 But sometimes also we forget, actually we don't forget, maybe we talk about this, we

216
00:11:57,340 --> 00:12:02,100
 don't really absorb this, that if it wasn't for Jesus and what He had done for us on the

217
00:12:02,100 --> 00:12:11,260
 cross, we too would be in the same position, vulnerable, hopeless, in need of a family.

218
00:12:11,260 --> 00:12:16,220
 And this is precisely why Jesus was sent by God onto this earth.

219
00:12:16,220 --> 00:12:21,740
 God sent His Son, born of a woman, born under the law, to redeem those under the law so

220
00:12:21,740 --> 00:12:24,060
 that we might receive what?

221
00:12:24,060 --> 00:12:27,540
 Adoption to sonship or daughtership.

222
00:12:27,540 --> 00:12:30,260
 God sending His Son was not an accident.

223
00:12:30,260 --> 00:12:36,740
 It was done with a plan and a purpose, for His intention for God to become our heavenly

224
00:12:36,740 --> 00:12:41,140
 Father, for that relationship to be reconciled.

225
00:12:41,140 --> 00:12:45,700
 God sending His Son means that our sin no longer separates us or estranges us from Him,

226
00:12:45,700 --> 00:12:49,540
 but rather we are adopted into His family.

227
00:12:49,540 --> 00:12:55,860
 God sending His Son was a way of His demonstrating His unconditional, very real love for us.

228
00:12:55,860 --> 00:13:01,820
 Before we did anything, God sent His Son to save us, to adopt us into His family, and

229
00:13:01,820 --> 00:13:05,300
 He continues to love us no matter what.

230
00:13:05,300 --> 00:13:11,340
 So yes, you and I are just as much as in need of these children I was talking about earlier,

231
00:13:11,340 --> 00:13:17,020
 to be adopted into a family, but into the family of God.

232
00:13:17,020 --> 00:13:21,220
