00:27:52,960 --> 00:27:55,760
 I find myself getting annoyed and frustrated at my parents.

473
00:27:55,760 --> 00:27:57,400
 You know, "Don't tell me what to do.

474
00:27:57,400 --> 00:27:59,080
 I'm a grown man.

475
00:27:59,080 --> 00:28:00,840
 I'm guilty of this all the time.

476
00:28:00,840 --> 00:28:02,520
 I'm getting better, but I still am.

477
00:28:02,520 --> 00:28:06,160
 A lot of the time when my mom calls, I just go, you pick up the phone.

478
00:28:06,160 --> 00:28:07,840
 I know what she's going to say too."

479
00:28:07,840 --> 00:28:08,840
 Uh-huh.

480
00:28:08,840 --> 00:28:09,840
 Yeah.

481
00:28:09,840 --> 00:28:10,840
 Okay.

482
00:28:10,840 --> 00:28:11,840
 Okay.

483
00:28:11,840 --> 00:28:12,840
 Okay.

484
00:28:12,840 --> 00:28:13,840
 Okay.

485
00:28:13,840 --> 00:28:14,840
 Okay.

486
00:28:14,840 --> 00:28:15,840
 Okay.

487
00:28:15,840 --> 00:28:16,840
 Okay.

488
00:28:16,840 --> 00:28:17,840
 Okay.

489
00:28:17,840 --> 00:28:18,840
 Bye-bye, you know, and that's it.

490
00:28:18,840 --> 00:28:19,840
 My aim is not to engage with her.

491
00:28:19,840 --> 00:28:21,680
 Okay, moms out there, okay?

492
00:28:21,680 --> 00:28:26,320
 My aim is to get her off the phone as fast as I can so I can return to what I'm doing.

493
00:28:26,320 --> 00:28:27,320
 Right?

494
00:28:27,320 --> 00:28:33,320
 It took my mom almost going to be with Jesus last year for me to start shifting my attitude

495
00:28:33,320 --> 00:28:35,520
 towards that.

496
00:28:35,520 --> 00:28:38,920
 So what does it mean to obey as children from one to 99?

497
00:28:38,920 --> 00:28:41,880
 What does it mean to obey our parents?

498
00:28:41,880 --> 00:28:48,720
 There's three things here I want us to do in an effort to enjoy and to be a better children

499
00:28:48,720 --> 00:28:49,880
 of our parents.

500
00:28:49,880 --> 00:28:54,440
 The three things are this, hearing, understanding, and responding.

501
00:28:54,440 --> 00:28:56,160
 So hearing.

502
00:28:56,160 --> 00:29:01,000
 Hearing is when we open our ears to what our parents have to say to us.

503
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:06,840
 Hearing means you remain in a posture of receiving when your parents are trying to talk to you.

504
00:29:06,840 --> 00:29:11,680
 Responding means you refrain from talking over them, from allowing them suitable time

505
00:29:11,680 --> 00:29:14,280
 and space to express themselves.

506
00:29:14,280 --> 00:29:16,340
 And this might not be easy, right?

507
00:29:16,340 --> 00:29:19,520
 You might have to learn how to hold your tongue.

508
00:29:19,520 --> 00:29:22,600
 You might have to learn how to control your anger.

509
00:29:22,600 --> 00:29:28,480
 But we must be able to hear our parents because without hearing, we cannot move on to step

510
00:29:28,480 --> 00:29:32,840
 two, which is understanding.

511
00:29:32,840 --> 00:29:39,040
 Understanding is a process of being able to fully put yourself in your parents' shoes.

512
00:29:39,040 --> 00:29:45,880
 Understanding is the ability to practice empathy, to look at situations from your parents' perspective,

513
00:29:45,880 --> 00:29:49,960
 to put down your own defenses and agenda.

514
00:29:49,960 --> 00:29:52,520
 Let me give you an example from my own life again.

515
00:29:52,520 --> 00:29:55,000
 My dad and I, I think we have a good relationship.

516
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:56,320
 We hang out, we go and eat.

517
00:29:56,320 --> 00:29:58,800
 We used to do a lot of trail running together.

518
00:29:58,800 --> 00:30:05,020
 He is an excellent dad, a man of honor, a man of integrity, a man of generosity.

519
00:30:05,020 --> 00:30:09,580
 But at the same time, growing up, I would admit I had a bit of a chip on my shoulder.

520
00:30:09,580 --> 00:30:12,920
 You know, because I would watch all these American movies where the dad would be like

521
00:30:12,920 --> 00:30:14,440
 super affectionate, right?

522
00:30:14,440 --> 00:30:17,640
 You get this, "Hey, sport, come over here," you know, and he like rubbed the child on

523
00:30:17,640 --> 00:30:21,120
 the head and give him a hug, say, "Okay, now, go get them, son."

524
00:30:21,120 --> 00:30:23,400
 And the son would be like full of confidence all of a sudden, right?

525
00:30:23,400 --> 00:30:27,160
 And go out there and do a slam dunk and hit the home run and everybody would be cheering

526
00:30:27,160 --> 00:30:30,920
 and like dad would come out again and hug them and it just looked like such a perfect

527
00:30:30,920 --> 00:30:33,640
 picture of what a father was like.

528
00:30:33,640 --> 00:30:37,440
 And I would feel resentful because like my dad's never said those things to me.

529
00:30:37,440 --> 00:30:38,440
 My dad has never told...

530
00:30:38,440 --> 00:30:42,040
 I've never heard the words, "I love you," come out of his mouth.

531
00:30:42,040 --> 00:30:44,960
 He's never given me a hug like that.

532
00:30:44,960 --> 00:30:46,440
 And I admit I would start to get resentful.

533
00:30:46,440 --> 00:30:50,960
 Well, how come my dad doesn't love me in that way?

534
00:30:50,960 --> 00:30:55,200
 There was a particular point in time where I became really angry about this amongst other

535
00:30:55,200 --> 00:30:56,500
 things.

536
00:30:56,500 --> 00:30:59,720
 There was a time of my life where as a young adult, I'd just come back to Hong Kong.

537
00:30:59,720 --> 00:31:03,440
 I was working through a deep season of depression.

538
00:31:03,440 --> 00:31:05,760
 I felt like nobody cared about me.

539
00:31:05,760 --> 00:31:09,320
 I felt like my dad was just being silent, ignoring me because he wouldn't engage with

540
00:31:09,320 --> 00:31:15,160
 me in conversation about my feelings until one night we were cooking dinner and my mom

541
00:31:15,160 --> 00:31:16,160
 talked to me.

542
00:31:16,160 --> 00:31:17,960
 I'll never forget what she said.

543
00:31:17,960 --> 00:31:19,600
 She said, "You know what?

544
00:31:19,600 --> 00:31:23,640
 You know, your dad has noticed that you've been acting different recently.

545
00:31:23,640 --> 00:31:27,820
 He's noticed that these days you're sad and he thinks you're going through a season of

546
00:31:27,820 --> 00:31:32,020
 depression and he's been praying for you.

547
00:31:32,020 --> 00:31:33,020
 He hasn't eaten...

548
00:31:33,020 --> 00:31:34,300
 He's fasted for the past three days.

549
00:31:34,300 --> 00:31:37,820
 He hasn't eaten a single thing for three days because he's been fasting and praying for

550
00:31:37,820 --> 00:31:38,820
 you."

551
00:31:38,820 --> 00:31:41,540
 I think I just wanted to know that, son.

552
00:31:41,540 --> 00:31:45,740
 I had no idea that was what he was doing.

553
00:31:45,740 --> 00:31:46,740
 And I got to think about it.

554
00:31:46,740 --> 00:31:50,660
 You see, what I failed to understand was my dad and his brothers never grew up with their

555
00:31:50,660 --> 00:31:51,660
 dad.

556
00:31:51,660 --> 00:31:54,460
 But his dad died when he was just a toddler.

557
00:31:54,460 --> 00:31:58,400
 My grandma raised six children on her own, single-handedly.

558
00:31:58,400 --> 00:31:59,900
 He never had his dad around.

559
00:31:59,900 --> 00:32:03,980
 He didn't have anyone to show him that kind of affection either.

560
00:32:03,980 --> 00:32:08,380
 And after coming to that understanding of where he was coming from, it helped me to

561
00:32:08,380 --> 00:32:13,040
 show honor and respect and to obey him better.

562
00:32:13,040 --> 00:32:16,180
 So we must seek to understand.

563
00:32:16,180 --> 00:32:18,780
 The final thing is this, responding.

564
00:32:18,780 --> 00:32:22,020
 Now responding is very different to reacting.

565
00:32:22,020 --> 00:32:23,420
 Reacting is almost like a reflex, right?

566
00:32:23,420 --> 00:32:24,660
 Someone pinches you, you say, "Ow."

567
00:32:24,660 --> 00:32:28,820
 Someone punches you, you turn the other cheek, right?

568
00:32:28,820 --> 00:32:30,260
 Okay.

569
00:32:30,260 --> 00:32:32,060
 Reacting is just instinctual.

570
00:32:32,060 --> 00:32:35,340
 In this context, reacting is when your parents talk to you, you just come back with whatever

571
00:32:35,340 --> 00:32:38,340
 you want to say that comes out of your mouth first.

572
00:32:38,340 --> 00:32:39,340
 That's reacting.

573
00:32:39,340 --> 00:32:42,380
 And often reacting is not helpful.

574
00:32:42,380 --> 00:32:44,700
 But responding.

575
00:32:44,700 --> 00:32:49,780
 Responding is what happens when we've gone through the process of hearing and understanding.

576
00:32:49,780 --> 00:32:55,900
 So that when we speak, our words, as Paul tells us later, can be full of grace, seasoned

577
00:32:55,900 --> 00:32:58,200
 with salt.

578
00:32:58,200 --> 00:33:03,460
 Responding is opening up to your parents, being able to have civil, calm conversations,

579
00:33:03,460 --> 00:33:07,040
 even on things that you might not agree with.

580
00:33:07,040 --> 00:33:11,700
 Responding is an act of love and honor to your parents.

581
00:33:12,700 --> 00:33:18,740
 Now, just as children are called to love and honor and obey their parents, parents are

582
00:33:18,740 --> 00:33:22,340
 now called to do the same for their children.

583
00:33:22,340 --> 00:33:23,340
 Let's read on.

584
00:33:23,340 --> 00:33:30,620
 "Fathers or mothers, parents, do not provoke your children, least they become discouraged."

585
00:33:30,620 --> 00:33:33,100
 Okay, this is a word for you parents.

586
00:33:33,100 --> 00:33:34,100
 This is your turn.

587
00:33:34,100 --> 00:33:36,020
 You guys were nodding your head, looking at your kids.

588
00:33:36,020 --> 00:33:38,060
 We're talking about obedience, okay?

589
00:33:38,060 --> 00:33:39,940
 Now here's a word for you.

590
00:33:39,940 --> 00:33:42,940
 Because there's mutual responsibility here.

591
00:33:42,940 --> 00:33:44,340
 And let me start by saying this.

592
00:33:44,340 --> 00:33:52,100
 We have to realize, parents, being a kid these days in Hong Kong is really, really tough.

593
00:33:52,100 --> 00:33:57,300
 It's no secret that almost from the day kids are born, we're born into a system that forces

594
00:33:57,300 --> 00:34:02,220
 kids to achieve from the time they're barely even able to walk.

595
00:34:02,220 --> 00:34:05,820
 You have to get into the right nursery so you get to the right kindergarten so you get

596
00:34:05,820 --> 00:34:09,500
 to the right primary school to get to the right high school, to get to the right university

597
00:34:09,500 --> 00:34:11,900
 so you can get the best job that you can.

598
00:34:11,900 --> 00:34:15,460
 So when you're still like pooping in your nappy, you're already being forced to make

599
00:34:15,460 --> 00:34:21,780
 life-changing, life-directing decisions from the time you're a baby.

600
00:34:21,780 --> 00:34:27,500
 It's a ridiculous system that a two-year-old has to go through an extensive interview to

601
00:34:27,500 --> 00:34:30,180
 enter into a school, okay?

602
00:34:30,180 --> 00:34:32,160
 Now again, don't hear me wrong.

603
00:34:32,160 --> 00:34:34,580
 I'm not anti-education.

604
00:34:34,580 --> 00:34:36,900
 I'm not saying that.

605
00:34:36,900 --> 00:34:41,340
 I'm not saying we shouldn't challenge our children to do hard things, to achieve, to

606
00:34:41,340 --> 00:34:42,580
 study hard.

607
00:34:42,580 --> 00:34:46,260
 All these things aren't bad in and of themselves.

608
00:34:46,260 --> 00:34:50,980
 But what an awful lot of pressure it is for a child to force them into doing things to

609
00:34:50,980 --> 00:34:53,980
 go through that kind of system.

610
00:34:53,980 --> 00:34:58,180
 Add this to the pressure, kids, from social media these days.

611
00:34:58,180 --> 00:35:00,540
 When I was growing up, there wasn't much social media.

612
00:35:00,540 --> 00:35:04,020
 I didn't grow up with smartphones and all that kind of stuff, so I can't even imagine

613
00:35:04,020 --> 00:35:10,820
 the impossible challenge of relating yourself with all these things you see on social media.

614
00:35:10,820 --> 00:35:16,020
 The very real, but behind-the-scenes cyberbullying that a lot of kids are going through.

615
00:35:16,020 --> 00:35:19,620
 The extracurricular activities that we force them to go through.

616
00:35:19,620 --> 00:35:23,340
 And recently, the changes in school schedules, in school, out of school, all these kind of

617
00:35:23,340 --> 00:35:24,420
 things.

618
00:35:24,420 --> 00:35:29,300
 Being a young person in Hong Kong is a difficult road.

619
00:35:29,300 --> 00:35:34,300
 So parents, let's take what scripture says here seriously.

620
00:35:34,300 --> 00:35:37,820
 Do not provoke our children.

621
00:35:37,820 --> 00:35:41,260
 The word provoke is called eretizo.

622
00:35:41,260 --> 00:35:45,140
 It means to make them become resentful.

623
00:35:45,140 --> 00:35:50,420
 So parents, in your effort to teach and educate your children, we have to be careful that

624
00:35:50,420 --> 00:35:54,820
 we too are respecting them as individuals.

625
00:35:54,820 --> 00:35:59,140
 One of the most amazing things about how God made us is that we are all unique.

626
00:35:59,140 --> 00:36:01,620
 We are all worthy in their eyes.

627
00:36:01,620 --> 00:36:06,700
 God loves us, and his love of us doesn't change no matter what.

628
00:36:06,700 --> 00:36:11,620
 God's favor upon his children is not tied up to what they can achieve.

629
00:36:11,620 --> 00:36:16,300
 So why do we sometimes place these expectations on our kids?

630
00:36:16,300 --> 00:36:21,560
 You know, Chinese parents, I know I'm stereotyping here, but one thing that bugs me so much every

631
00:36:21,560 --> 00:36:27,300
 time I hear it, when I hear the words from a parent to a child, "Ah, you're useless."

632
00:36:27,300 --> 00:36:30,620
 You are useless.

633
00:36:30,620 --> 00:36:33,100
 Parents say this all the time in this city, and it's a problem.

634
00:36:33,100 --> 00:36:37,220
 We need to stop tying up our children with what they can achieve.

635
00:36:37,220 --> 00:36:42,380
 But did you know a recent study showed that only half of secondary school students in

636
00:36:42,380 --> 00:36:44,940
 Hong Kong show signs of depression?

637
00:36:44,940 --> 00:36:50,740
 Seventy percent of students in Hong Kong reported that they have a bad relationship with their

638
00:36:50,740 --> 00:36:51,740
 parents.

639
00:36:51,740 --> 00:36:54,060
 This should break our hearts.

640
00:36:54,060 --> 00:36:59,380
 It should really make us think as parents, ask ourselves, "How do we contribute to this?

641
00:36:59,380 --> 00:37:03,540
 And how do we demonstrate God's love to our children?"

642
00:37:03,540 --> 00:37:06,660
 So here again are a few suggestions.

643
00:37:06,660 --> 00:37:09,080
 Get to know your child.

644
00:37:09,080 --> 00:37:13,420
 As the parent, yes, you are the parent, but how well do you truly know your child?

645
00:37:13,420 --> 00:37:15,980
 How much time are we spending with them?

646
00:37:15,980 --> 00:37:20,300
 Asking about their interests, asking them about their feelings, their hopes, their dreams.

647
00:37:20,300 --> 00:37:25,660
 These are great conversations to engage with your child regularly.

648
00:37:25,660 --> 00:37:26,660
 Acknowledge their efforts.

649
00:37:26,660 --> 00:37:33,900
 Again, achievement is not a bad thing in itself, but when everything is tied up to achievement,

650
00:37:33,900 --> 00:37:36,800
 that becomes a lot of pressure.

651
00:37:36,800 --> 00:37:40,280
 When our kids do good things, yes, let's celebrate it.

652
00:37:40,280 --> 00:37:42,700
 Don't just take it for granted.

653
00:37:42,700 --> 00:37:48,140
 But when they fail to achieve our expectations, celebrate their efforts.

654
00:37:48,140 --> 00:37:49,860
 Tell them, "Well done."

655
00:37:49,860 --> 00:37:52,940
 Tell them, "Good job."

656
00:37:52,940 --> 00:37:55,440
 Challenge and teach them to try again.

657
00:37:55,440 --> 00:38:00,420
 And let's never use shame to motivate our children to do better.

658
00:38:00,420 --> 00:38:07,500
 God never puts us to shame, so we should never do this to our children as well.

659
00:38:07,500 --> 00:38:09,340
 Finally it's this.

660
00:38:09,340 --> 00:38:11,700
 Remind them of their worth.

661
00:38:11,700 --> 00:38:14,280
 Children need to hear that they're good enough.

662
00:38:14,280 --> 00:38:18,980
 They need to be reassured that their worth is never and will never ever be tied up with

663
00:38:18,980 --> 00:38:20,740
 what they can do.

664
00:38:20,740 --> 00:38:25,060
 They need to know that failing is okay, that it's not the end, but rather we learn from

665
00:38:25,060 --> 00:38:28,000
 our failures and we move on.

666
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:31,700
 And ultimately as parents, just as husbands and wives are called to demonstrate an example

667
00:38:31,700 --> 00:38:36,700
 of the gracious love of God to each other, when your child looks to you, our goal for

668
00:38:36,700 --> 00:38:42,980
 them is to give them a glimpse of what the Father's love for us might look like.

669
00:38:42,980 --> 00:38:46,880
 And here's the really beautiful thing.

670
00:38:46,880 --> 00:38:51,280
 When families are working as God intended them to work, when husbands and wives are

671
00:38:51,280 --> 00:38:55,680
 loving each other, when children are obeying their parents, parents are empowering the

672
00:38:55,680 --> 00:38:58,480
 children, God is pleased.

673
00:38:58,480 --> 00:39:02,680
 And the generations are blessed through such families.

674
00:39:02,680 --> 00:39:06,940
 Deuteronomy 7, 9, "The Lord your God is your God.

675
00:39:06,940 --> 00:39:12,240
 He is the faithful God, keeping his covenant of love to a thousand generations of those

676
00:39:12,240 --> 00:39:16,000
 who love him and keep his commandments."

677
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:21,860
 God is faithful to building healthy, good families.

678
00:39:21,860 --> 00:39:25,600
 Let me show you how by tying this all together.

679
00:39:25,600 --> 00:39:29,440
 I started this message by telling you about baby Sam, our foster baby.

680
00:39:29,440 --> 00:39:34,240
 Well, like I said, about nine months with us, he was matched to a family and we had

681
00:39:34,240 --> 00:39:39,920
 the privilege of going through the gut-wrenching, heart-wrenching process of helping him transition

682
00:39:39,920 --> 00:39:43,500
 out of our home into his forever family.

683
00:39:43,500 --> 00:39:47,720
 And saying goodbye to baby Sam will forever be one of the hardest things that we've ever

684
00:39:47,720 --> 00:39:50,160
 had to do as a family.

685
00:39:50,160 --> 00:39:51,820
 But you know what?

686
00:39:51,820 --> 00:39:54,240
 Throughout this process, we had one prayer.

687
00:39:54,240 --> 00:40:00,160
 Our prayer was that Sam would be adopted into a loving, healthy family and that somehow

688
00:40:00,160 --> 00:40:04,680
 we would be able to stay in touch and be a part of his life.

689
00:40:04,680 --> 00:40:10,600
 Well, just like God showed us his love by adopting us into his family, Sam was adopted

690
00:40:10,600 --> 00:40:16,000
 into the most perfect, beautiful family that I believe God was preparing for him.

691
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:21,240
 He has parents that love him so well that are raising him up.

692
00:40:21,240 --> 00:40:28,480
 What might have been a story of brokenness has transformed into a story of redemption.

693
00:40:28,480 --> 00:40:33,000
 But here's something even cooler.

694
00:40:33,000 --> 00:40:38,160
 Not long after Sam left our home, God gave us our own child, Isaiah, whom I hope we're

695
00:40:38,160 --> 00:40:44,720
 raising in a family that's filled with love and the presence of God is this as well.

696
00:40:44,720 --> 00:40:46,400
 And God answered our prayer.

697
00:40:46,400 --> 00:40:49,680
 He gave us even more than we could imagine or ask for.

698
00:40:49,680 --> 00:40:55,280
 He even answered our prayer by allowing us to stay in touch with Sam and his family.

699
00:40:55,280 --> 00:40:59,640
 And here's this picture of Sam now as a grown boy praying with our boy, Isaiah, just a couple

700
00:40:59,640 --> 00:41:01,280
 of months ago.

701
00:41:01,280 --> 00:41:07,520
 Look at those cheeky faces, right?

702
00:41:07,520 --> 00:41:10,540
 God loves families.

703
00:41:10,540 --> 00:41:16,440
 He loves your family and he wants to see the brokenness in your family healed.

704
00:41:16,440 --> 00:41:23,880
 He wants to see the generations of his love being passed down through the generations.

705
00:41:23,880 --> 00:41:29,520
 So my prayer is that every family here today, no matter what it looks like for you, would

706
00:41:29,520 --> 00:41:32,240
 truly know God and his love.

707
00:41:32,240 --> 00:41:37,280
 I pray that we would learn how to love our family members and that we would find the

708
00:41:37,280 --> 00:41:42,640
 remedy of a broken relationship within our families through loving each other as God

709
00:41:42,640 --> 00:41:44,240
 has loved us.

710
00:41:44,240 --> 00:41:49,420
 And that through this, God would display his faithfulness through the generations until

